								<div class="title" id="post-title-4548902">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/sharpembrace" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(6032914); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=6032914&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610252026" alt="SharpEmbrace" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=6032914)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/sharpembrace" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(6032914); return false;" >SharpEmbrace</a></span> <span class="odate time_1584286039 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">15 Mar 2020 15:27</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4548902">
									

<p>I really want to like this. I really do. The concept is compelling and the story could be heart-wrenching. I just can't bring myself to upvote or even novote something so full of prose errors. I understand that this is a Jam-Con entry and such things are to be expected but here it makes reading somewhat arduous. I can't enjoy this story if I'm frustrated by the rushed prose.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">grammatical&nbsp;errors</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">jeez&nbsp;that's&nbsp;a&nbsp;lot</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>The main issue is that there's an abundance of punctuation misuse. I'm not going to list them all but I'll show some of the most egregious examples.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Hearing the sound of shoes above her head he froze, the steady beat of the foreman's boots as they plodded along the gridded metal.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>There should be a second comma after head. Also, this should be <strong>she</strong> froze and there is a missing verb. A rewritten sentence would be <em>Hearing footsteps above her head, she froze, petrified by the steady beat of the foreman's boots.</em></p>
<blockquote>
<p>He was the gear that oiled the machine; the man of finances.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Semicolons should be followed by main clauses and not noun phrases like this. It would make sense to replace this semicolon with a colon.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The white and black slips quickly turning red and being crushed beneath the press of bodies.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This should really be a subordinate clause connected to the prior sentence as it makes no sense as a main clause on its own.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Perhaps it would serve as an example to the rest, may improve their productivity he pondered.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>There's a dialogue tag here but it lacks quotation marks. Even so, this is poorly phrased.<br />
<em>&quot;Perhaps, it would serve as an example to the others; seeing this punishment might improve their productivity.&quot; he said.</em> would be better.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The grinding of the factory floor below was beginning to get on his nerves, it was probably time to return to his office upstairs.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Comma splice. This comma should be a semicolon as there are two main clauses.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">other&nbsp;issues</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">it's&nbsp;not&nbsp;*that*&nbsp;bad</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>There are a couple of unusually phrased sentences and peculiar word choices here and there but this not as big an issue as the grammar.</p>
<p>For example,</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;Hello there, are you going somewhere perhaps?&quot; a stern voice said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This is hardly stern dialogue and this speech creates a lot of cognitive dissonance regarding the character of the Coinmaster. <em>&quot;Where do you think you're going, little girl?&quot; said a stern voice from behind her.</em> would be more effective for characterisation.</p>
<p>Also,</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The grinding of the factory floor below was beginning to get on his nerves, it was probably time to return to his office upstairs.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This makes no sense. Why is he averse to the sounds and horrors of the Factory in one paragraph and say it's delicious in the next?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>He slowly walked forward. Like a predator tracking it's prey.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>First of all, this should be its rather than it's. Moreover, this is again an example of a subordinate clause being written on its own. I am also not a fan of literally saying that he is akin to a predator as opposed to comparing him to a specific animal or just conveying it through word choice. Especially as walked doesn't convey his predatory nature the way stalked or pursued would.</p>
<p>Another thing I find problematic is the repetitive sentence structure, which I find jarring. Like, half of your sentences are &quot;blah blah describing action, action.&quot; or &quot;action, blah blah describing action&quot;</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Overall, the structure and concept behind this are rock-solid. The execution, however, doesn't reach the same standard.</p>
<p>edit: now a novote because the mentioned issues have been fixed</p>

							</div>

