				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/blackbattleship" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(6150316); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=6150316&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610252026" alt="BlackBattleship" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=6150316)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/blackbattleship" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(6150316); return false;" >BlackBattleship</a></span> <span class="odate time_1588951247 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">08 May 2020 15:20</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4636756">
									

<p>Really liked this tale. A solid concept, has a strong atmosphere and the parallelism worked here really well.<br />
Made a few edits to it, but there are still some sentences that I found odd. In particular,</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The cost of repairs was next on his list, and God knows it needed doing.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>What needed doing were repairs and not the cost, so it's &quot;they needed doing&quot;. Also, while it's grammatically correct, &quot;needed doing&quot; sounds too complex and jarring to me. I think &quot;The cost of repairs was next on his list, and God knows they were needed&quot; or something along those lines would be better. I can see, however, that you might be going for that heavier tone here, so it's more of a personal preference.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The alchemic molecular printers had needed a clean and fix for a while he mused.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Why perfect tense? As I see it, the printers still need cleaning, nothing has been done to them yet. When you use past perfect you're implying something happened after the event (or, in this, case, state) described.</p>
<p>Other then that, again, liked the story, upvote from me.</p>

							</div>

								
